FR941116-2-00073 FR941116-2-00059 Employment and Training Administration Notice of Determinations Regarding Eligibility To Apply for Worker Adjustment Assistance and NAFTA Transitional Adjustment Assistance In accordance with Section 223 of the Trade Act of 1974, as amended, the Department of Labor herein presents summaries of determinations regarding eligibility to apply for trade adjustment assistance for workers (TA&hyph;W) issued during the period of November, 1994. In order for an affirmative determination to be made and a certification of eligibility to apply for worker adjustment assistance to be issued, each of the group eligibility requirements of Section 222 of the Act must be met. (1) That a significant number or proportion of the workers in the workers' firm, or an appropriate subdivision thereof, have become totally or partially separated, (2) That sales or production, or both, of the firm or subdivision have decreased absolutely, and (3) That increases of imports of articles like or directly competitive with articles produced by the firm or appropriate subdivision have contributed importantly to the separations, or threat thereof, and to the absolute decline in sales or production. Negative Determinations for Worker Adjustment Assistance In each of the following cases the investigation revealed that criterion (3) has not been met. A survey of customers indicated that increased imports did not contribute importantly to worker separations at the firm. TA&hyph;W&hyph;30,112; Atlas Building Systems, Inc., Marlton, NJ TA&hyph;W&hyph;30,206; Schlegel of Maryland, Inc., Chestertown, MD TA&hyph;W&hyph;29,950; S.D. Warren Co., Westbrook, ME TA&hyph;W&hyph;30,269; Highland Yarn Mills, High Point, NC In the following cases, the investigation revealed that the criteria for eligibility have not been met for the reasons specified. TA&hyph;W&hyph;30,443; Shimazaki Corp., Port Newark, NJ The workers' firm does not produce an article as required for certification under Section 222 of the Trade Act of 1974. TA&hyph;W&hyph;30,422; Rome Cable Corp., Rome, NY Increased imports did not contribute importantly to worker separations at the firm. TA&hyph;W&hyph;30,312; Carr Well Service, Odessa, TX The workers' firm does not produce an article as required for certification under Section 222 of the Trade Act of 1974. TA&hyph;W&hyph;30,265; LAN Technologies, Inc., Bedford, MA The predominate reason for the layoff of workers at LAN Technologies, Inc., Bedford, MA was due to a corporate decision to move its production facility from Bedford, MA to Pueblo, CO in October 1994. TA&hyph;W&hyph;30,185; General Dynamics Land System, Inc., Sterling Heights, MI The investigation revealed that the US Government does not purchase battle tanks from foreign manufacturers. TA&hyph;W&hyph;30,332; Intera Information Technologies, Inc., Denver, CO The workers' firm does not produce an article as required for certification under Section 222 of the Trade Act of 1974. TA&hyph;W&hyph;30,134; Sea Farm Washington, Inc., DBA Stolt Sea Farm, Inc., Port Angeles, WA The workers' firm does not produce an article as required for certification under Section 222 of the Trade Act of 1974. TA&hyph;W&hyph;30,175; Bayflux Fabrics, Inc., Lincoln Park, NJ Increased imports did not contribute importantly to worker separations at the firm. TA&hyph;W&hyph;30,340; Moran Towing of Pennsylvania, Philadelphia, PA TA&hyph;W&hyph;30,341; McAllister Brothers, Inc., Camden, NJ The workers' firm does not produce an article as required for certification under Section 222 of the Trade Act of 1974. TA&hyph;W&hyph;30,330; National Oilwell, Houston, TX The workers' firm does not produce an article as required for certification under Section 222 of the Trade Act of 1974. TA&hyph;W&hyph;30,288; Beth Energy Mines Corp., Cambria Slope, Mine # 33, Ebensburg, PA Aggregate US imports of coal are negligible during the relevant period. TA&hyph;W&hyph;30,342; Linmar Petroleum Co., Roosevelt, UT The workers' firm does not produce an article as required for certification under Section 222 of the Trade Act of 1974. Affirmative Determinations for Worker Adjustment Assistance TA&hyph;W&hyph;30,278; Ward Paper Co., A Div. of International Paper, Merrill, WI A certification was issued covering all workers separated on or after August 23, 1993. TA&hyph;W&hyph;30,395; Charter Production Co., Wichita, KS A certification was issued covering all workers separated on or after September 27, 1993.
